b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48284.htm)  [Next](sbe48286.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n39\\. And as the carpenter, in both ways.\n\nThe Self, although always provided with the instruments of action, such as the\norgan of speech, and so on, acts when it wishes to do so, and does not act\nwhen it does not wish to do so. Just as a carpenter, although having his axe\nand other implements ready at hand, works or does not work just as he pleases.\nIf the internal organ, on the contrary, were essentially active, it would\nconstantly be acting, since as a non-intelligent being it could not be\ninfluenced by particular reasons for action, such as the desire for enjoyment.\n\nHere terminates the adhikara _n_ a of 'the agent.'\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 40. But from the highest, this being declared by\nScripture](sbe48286.htm)\n\n"